00:00:00.680 --> 00:00:04.730
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress in Washington, DC.

00:00:18.610 --> 00:00:19.910
&gt;&gt; Betsy Peterson:
I'm Betsy Peterson.

00:00:19.910 --> 00:00:22.540
I'm the director of the
American Folklife Center

00:00:22.540 --> 00:00:23.840
and I want to say welcome.

00:00:23.840 --> 00:00:26.570
We're really thrilled
that you all are here.

00:00:26.570 --> 00:00:30.920
This is Collections,
Collaborations and Connections.

00:00:30.920 --> 00:00:34.040
I guess every academics sort

00:00:34.040 --> 00:00:37.500
of gathering must have
a literation somewhere

00:00:37.500 --> 00:00:40.250
in some title, with a colon.

00:00:40.250 --> 00:00:42.320
So we're doing our best.

00:00:42.320 --> 00:00:47.800
But this is an event looking at
the American Folklife Center at 40.

00:00:47.800 --> 00:00:51.990
And we're really thrilled to
be having this opportunity

00:00:51.990 --> 00:00:55.280
to celebrate all of the good work
of the American Folklife Center

00:00:55.280 --> 00:00:57.530
over the course of the whole year.

00:00:57.530 --> 00:01:01.700
This is the third of three
symposiums that we've hosted

00:01:01.700 --> 00:01:05.800
over the last couple of years
examining various issues related

00:01:05.800 --> 00:01:08.220
to cultural heritage documentation

00:01:08.220 --> 00:01:12.000
and archival practice
in this new century.

00:01:12.000 --> 00:01:15.970 position:56%
And while we wanted to celebrate the
work of the American Folklife Center

00:01:15.970 --> 00:01:19.660
and celebrate the collections
of the American Folklife Center,

00:01:19.660 --> 00:01:23.190
we also wanted to do much more
than that over the next two days.

00:01:23.190 --> 00:01:30.760
And in developing the agenda, the
AFC staff working on the symposium,

00:01:30.760 --> 00:01:35.660
Nancy Groce, Guha Shankar,
Nikki Saylor and myself,

00:01:35.660 --> 00:01:40.080
we decided to highlight a handful
of our collections with an emphasis

00:01:40.080 --> 00:01:44.620
on work developed since
the AFC's founding in 1976,

00:01:44.620 --> 00:01:47.790
though that's by no mean--
no means exclusively.

00:01:47.790 --> 00:01:53.720
As you can see from the large wax
cylinder collections documenting

00:01:53.720 --> 00:01:58.060
Native American song from the turn
of the 20th century all the way

00:01:58.060 --> 00:02:01.720
to our latest efforts to
develop a digital folklore web

00:02:01.720 --> 00:02:03.970
archiving project.

00:02:03.970 --> 00:02:06.350
We also selected these collections

00:02:06.350 --> 00:02:09.030
with an eye towards
inviting discussions

00:02:09.030 --> 00:02:12.620
about contemporary problems
in archival practice

00:02:12.620 --> 00:02:15.460 position:56%
and cultural heritage documentation.

00:02:15.460 --> 00:02:17.690
And for us, some of
these problems focus

00:02:17.690 --> 00:02:21.820
on revisiting analog
collections, wax cylinders,

00:02:21.820 --> 00:02:24.570 position:56%
making them accessible in a new era.

00:02:24.570 --> 00:02:28.670
Some involve the thorny issues of
working with born digital material

00:02:28.670 --> 00:02:31.840
and capturing emergent
vernacular culture.

00:02:31.840 --> 00:02:34.350
Others involve very thorny issues

00:02:34.350 --> 00:02:39.060
of collaboration authority inviting
multiple voices into the archives

00:02:39.060 --> 00:02:45.520
and inviting multiple uses of
our archives as we go forward.

00:02:45.520 --> 00:02:49.270
All of them require us to
think about scalability

00:02:49.270 --> 00:02:51.220
and the scope of our work.

00:02:51.220 --> 00:02:56.220
I imagine these are problems
all of us encounter every day

00:02:56.220 --> 00:02:58.250
in our work in some fashion.

00:02:58.250 --> 00:03:03.440
So we're looking forward to some
very lively challenging discussion.

00:03:03.440 --> 00:03:06.190
We hope you will think
out loud with us.

00:03:06.190 --> 00:03:11.700
We do not see this as a
symposium where we tell you

00:03:11.700 --> 00:03:13.230
