00:08:02.510 --> 00:08:06.370
[ Applause ]

00:08:06.370 --> 00:08:09.070
What-- this is-- so
this is a paragraph.

00:08:09.070 --> 00:08:12.160
It was called-- it's from a
piece called Building an Archives

00:08:12.160 --> 00:08:13.460
for the Future.

00:08:13.460 --> 00:08:17.080
Folklife Center celebrates
its 20th anniversary.

00:08:17.080 --> 00:08:22.540
And he also sort of sets
the context for that event.

00:08:22.540 --> 00:08:26.950
The 1970s was a period of
increased attention to roots.

00:08:26.950 --> 00:08:30.530
Those aspects of heritage that
lie between the individual

00:08:30.530 --> 00:08:33.620
and the nation and the
connect individuals

00:08:33.620 --> 00:08:37.590
to communities while defining
the nation as a whole.

00:08:37.590 --> 00:08:39.580
This attention led to the passage

00:08:39.580 --> 00:08:44.810 position:56%
of the American Folklife
Preservation Act, Public Law 94-201,

00:08:44.810 --> 00:08:50.420
that passed both houses of Congress
at the end of 1975 and was signed

00:08:50.420 --> 00:08:56.030
into law by President
Ford on January 2nd, 1976.

00:08:56.030 --> 00:08:57.600
The definition of folklife

00:08:57.600 --> 00:09:01.500 position:56%
in the American Folklife
Preservation Act anchored the center

00:09:01.500 --> 00:09:06.050
firmly in the expressive culture
of the family, ethnic, religious,

00:09:06.050 --> 00:09:10.860
occupational and regional
groups that make up America.

00:09:10.860 --> 00:09:16.910
I tried to think with what that
paragraph would be like in 2016

00:09:16.910 --> 00:09:19.650
and it would be very different.

00:09:19.650 --> 00:09:24.890
And I think the shifts are striking
and I think the shifts will speak

00:09:24.890 --> 00:09:29.220
to some of these dramatic
changes, and some of the things

00:09:29.220 --> 00:09:31.940
that shape our work
now going forward.

00:09:31.940 --> 00:09:36.330
And certainly, I think we see
very dramatic shifts in attitude

00:09:36.330 --> 00:09:39.390
and a tempered belief in
the national enterprise

00:09:39.390 --> 00:09:43.170
and democratic experiment
that is the United States.

00:09:43.170 --> 00:09:46.260
I think there are shifts in
expectations about government

00:09:46.260 --> 00:09:51.130
and civil society, citizen
rights, and responsibilities.

00:09:51.130 --> 00:09:53.700
I think there is a stronger
push towards the limit

00:09:53.700 --> 00:09:56.200 position:56%
of government and fiscal constraint.

00:09:56.200 --> 00:09:59.410
And these shifts have
affected and continued

00:09:59.410 --> 00:10:04.100
to affect how we do our work, how
we conduct our field research,

00:10:04.100 --> 00:10:08.170 position:56%
how we develop our collections and
they affect our access to resources.

00:10:08.170 --> 00:10:10.740
And I think know, Alan began

00:10:10.740 --> 00:10:16.120
to experience those
constraints towards the end

00:10:16.120 --> 00:10:20.380
of his 20-year period
here at the Library.

00:10:20.380 --> 00:10:23.810
There's also been a shift from
analog to digital and the rise

00:10:23.810 --> 00:10:29.130
of the internet and social
media of course are critical.

00:10:29.130 --> 00:10:33.020
And the technology for
documenting our lives

00:10:33.020 --> 00:10:35.010
and culture is much cheaper.

00:10:35.010 --> 00:10:36.310
There's more of it.

00:10:36.310 --> 00:10:38.770
It's available and
accessible to all.

00:10:38.770 --> 00:10:42.140
And we can document most
anything anywhere anytime.

00:10:42.140 --> 00:10:45.490
And these shifts make
it possible for anyone

00:10:45.490 --> 00:10:48.610
to do professional
quality documentation

00:10:48.610 --> 00:10:52.050
and approximate archival standards.

00:10:52.050 --> 00:10:54.820
And it puts into play
all sorts of questions

00:10:54.820 --> 00:10:58.540
about professional knowledge,
authoritative expertise,

00:10:58.540 --> 00:11:01.980
and it also allows us to
begin thinking about access

00:11:01.980 --> 00:11:05.070
on a scale never before possible.

00:11:05.070 --> 00:11:09.730
And ironically, as it calls into
question professional expertise,

00:11:09.730 --> 00:11:14.410
it also requires a whole new set
of skills and expertise to deal

00:11:14.410 --> 00:11:19.160
with this work in the
backend of things.

00:11:19.160 --> 00:11:22.180
Closer to our disciplinary
foundations, there are shifts

00:11:22.180 --> 00:11:24.680
and ideas about community
and individual.

00:11:24.680 --> 00:11:30.290
And in the 1970s, as you
could see from that statement

00:11:30.290 --> 00:11:35.300
in the definition of Folklife
and the way it was portrayed,

00:11:35.300 --> 00:11:39.100 position:56%
there was more emphasis on
describing cultural or social groups

00:11:39.100 --> 00:11:42.860
in monolithic or static terms.

00:11:42.860 --> 00:11:45.450
And in the intervening
years, there is a greater--

00:11:45.450 --> 00:11:48.320
there's been a greater
acknowledgment in anthropology,

00:11:48.320 --> 00:11:53.530
sociology, folklore, most any
place you look in the agency

00:11:53.530 --> 00:11:56.930
of the individual, and
the evolving processes

00:11:56.930 --> 00:12:00.370
of forging individual identity.

00:12:00.370 --> 00:12:03.360
The shift from group to
individuals almost moved

00:12:03.360 --> 00:12:06.050
from individual towards group.

00:12:06.050 --> 00:12:10.150
These shifts affect how we
think about folk culture today.

00:12:10.150 --> 00:12:12.770
They affect how we think
about cultural communities

00:12:12.770 --> 00:12:14.860
and individual creativity.

00:12:14.860 --> 00:12:18.250
And it affects the type
of collections we develop.

00:12:18.250 --> 00:12:22.740
World history collections have
always been a part of the archive,

00:12:22.740 --> 00:12:26.690
but are increasing in number
and significance as a part

00:12:26.690 --> 00:12:29.130
of the archive, and the
Veterans History Project,

00:12:29.130 --> 00:12:32.130
and the Civil Rights
History project,

00:12:32.130 --> 00:12:36.830
both are congressionally mandated
projects are recent examples.

00:12:36.830 --> 00:12:39.600
And I can't believe I'm
talking as much I am.

00:12:39.600 --> 00:12:41.130
I've just gotten my morning.

00:12:41.130 --> 00:12:47.020
From the AFC's beginnings,
Alan with Carl Fleischhauer,

00:12:47.020 --> 00:12:52.210
who was also in our midst and was
the first staff member hired here

00:12:52.210 --> 00:12:58.040
at the center, I know both of them
saw a direct linkage to the archive

00:12:58.040 --> 00:13:03.080
of folk song, which was
founded by the Library in 1928.

00:13:03.080 --> 00:13:05.630
And in fact, the AFC was
placed at the Library in part

00:13:05.630 --> 00:13:09.080
because the archive of
folk song existed here.

00:13:09.080 --> 00:13:13.380
The archive eventually merged
with AFC beginning in 1978

00:13:13.380 --> 00:13:16.820
and it is still the
heart of AFC, I think.

00:13:16.820 --> 00:13:20.290
But the archive had a legacy
of initiating field research,

00:13:20.290 --> 00:13:23.500
sending government workers
out, solo or as part

00:13:23.500 --> 00:13:25.880
of larger federal projects
such as the WPA.

00:13:25.880 --> 00:13:31.190
And in the first 10 years of the
center, this was a large part

00:13:31.190 --> 00:13:32.860
of the work that the center did.

00:13:32.860 --> 00:13:36.920
And while they were
continuing in a tradition,

00:13:36.920 --> 00:13:38.880
they were also adding to it.

00:13:38.880 --> 00:13:43.550
And they were developing team-based
approaches to field research

00:13:43.550 --> 00:13:46.540
and the material was
much broader in scope,

00:13:46.540 --> 00:13:50.590 position:56%
while I think the earlier material
was much more sort of item oriented,

00:13:50.590 --> 00:13:55.270
focusing on getting those
songs, getting those stories,

00:13:55.270 --> 00:13:59.820 position:56%
this field work was much more
focused on documenting a broad range

00:13:59.820 --> 00:14:02.970
of cultural tradition
in everyday life.

00:14:02.970 --> 00:14:07.400
And visual documentation became
very central to the process

00:14:07.400 --> 00:14:12.180
and has only continued
to grow and be at present

00:14:12.180 --> 00:14:14.740
as much as or audio material.

00:14:14.740 --> 00:14:17.420
In the late '80s, federal
budget shrunk,

00:14:17.420 --> 00:14:20.660
field surveys decreased
in size and number.

00:14:20.660 --> 00:14:27.010
And programming started becoming
more critical and, I'm almost done.

00:14:27.010 --> 00:14:29.920
I promise.

00:14:29.920 --> 00:14:32.340
Alan has remarked that
in that period,

00:14:32.340 --> 00:14:36.170
there began to be a
shift towards working

00:14:36.170 --> 00:14:38.320
with the collections that existed.

00:14:38.320 --> 00:14:41.350
And I think the Federal
Cylinder Project and the work

00:14:41.350 --> 00:14:45.090
that is continuing to be
done to bring that work

00:14:45.090 --> 00:14:49.600
into the 21st century
is one great example,

00:14:49.600 --> 00:14:52.580
and a very successful
example of that.

00:14:52.580 --> 00:14:58.330
When Peggy Bulger came to the
archive in the Folklife Center

00:14:58.330 --> 00:15:05.710
in 1998, she shifted-- began to
shift some of the collecting,

00:15:05.710 --> 00:15:09.030
or collections development
for the Folklife Center.

00:15:09.030 --> 00:15:12.770 position:56%
And again, I think fiscal constraint
and limited government begins

00:15:12.770 --> 00:15:16.330
to come into play into
that equation and began

00:15:16.330 --> 00:15:20.010 position:56%
to acquire collections either
through donation or through purchase

00:15:20.010 --> 00:15:24.110
from individuals such as
Alan Lomax, John Cohen,

00:15:24.110 --> 00:15:26.450
Bruce Jackson, Margaret Mills.

00:15:26.450 --> 00:15:29.870
And she also began to
develop long-term agreements

00:15:29.870 --> 00:15:34.460
with nonprofit organizations
such as StoryCorps,

00:15:34.460 --> 00:15:38.010
the International Storytelling
Center, the National Council

00:15:38.010 --> 00:15:40.460
for the Traditional
Arts and more recently,

00:15:40.460 --> 00:15:43.530
the Center for Traditional
Music and Dance.

00:15:43.530 --> 00:15:48.170
And as Steve Winick has commented
in a blog, this led to an explosion

00:15:48.170 --> 00:15:51.220
in the quantity of
documentation in the archive

