00:37:40.190 --> 00:37:43.040
So, I'm one of the
principal investigators

00:37:43.040 --> 00:37:46.240
on a project called
Documenting the Now

00:37:46.240 --> 00:37:49.290
and we're building a
social media archiving tool

00:37:49.290 --> 00:37:51.270
that were calling DocNow.

00:37:51.270 --> 00:37:55.770
This is a partnership
project with Washington,

00:37:55.770 --> 00:37:58.450
University of Saint Louis and
also the Maryland Institute

00:37:58.450 --> 00:38:00.260
for Technology and the Humanities.

00:38:00.260 --> 00:38:05.760
My other two PIs are at summers,
who is the lead software developer

00:38:05.760 --> 00:38:11.840
at MITH in Maryland and Chris
Freeland at Washington University.

00:38:11.840 --> 00:38:17.310
This work started a couple of
years ago with Ed Summers and I.

00:38:17.310 --> 00:38:22.130
This project was really inspired
by the events following the killing

00:38:22.130 --> 00:38:27.980
of Michael Brown in Ferguson
Missouri in August 2014.

00:38:27.980 --> 00:38:31.970
And, you know, the millions of
images that we saw being shared

00:38:31.970 --> 00:38:36.200
on Twitter and other social
media spaces, millions of videos,

00:38:36.200 --> 00:38:43.000
personal stories about that
event and what it led to.

00:38:43.000 --> 00:38:46.010
So we saw these millions
of expressions of--

00:38:46.010 --> 00:38:50.700
sort of publicly accessible
expressions of grief, of anger,

00:38:50.700 --> 00:38:55.520
of criticism, of support and, you
know, Ferguson is what really led

00:38:55.520 --> 00:39:01.070
to what we now know as-- what
gave life to what we know

00:39:01.070 --> 00:39:04.220
as the Black Lives Matter
movement right now, right,

00:39:04.220 --> 00:39:07.220
which is a movement that sort
of bring us more attention

00:39:07.220 --> 00:39:10.220
to mass incarceration,
police violence

00:39:10.220 --> 00:39:12.430
in poor communities,
among other things.

00:39:12.430 --> 00:39:15.760
And so, you know, we
were at the Young Society

00:39:15.760 --> 00:39:17.590
of American Archivist
conference during the week

00:39:17.590 --> 00:39:20.220
that Michael Brown was killed
and it was basically a bunch

00:39:20.220 --> 00:39:23.430 position:56%
of archivists sort of sitting around
watching these events sort of fall

00:39:23.430 --> 00:39:27.580
in social media and thinking about
ways that we could help, you know,

00:39:27.580 --> 00:39:30.990
our peers collect this
information, build documentation,

00:39:30.990 --> 00:39:32.980
builds collections around this type

00:39:32.980 --> 00:39:37.030
of very rich content
that was being shared.

00:39:37.030 --> 00:39:42.080
And so, we decided to start
doing several projects

00:39:42.080 --> 00:39:45.510
around collecting different
hashtags, around killings

00:39:45.510 --> 00:39:48.920
that were happening that
happened over the past two years,

00:39:48.920 --> 00:39:52.250
we had Walter Scott, we had
the Charleston shooting,

00:39:52.250 --> 00:39:54.440
we had Sandra Bland.

00:39:54.440 --> 00:39:58.140
All of these different types of
events had their own life online

00:39:58.140 --> 00:40:00.760
and they were really sort of
playing out on social media,

00:40:00.760 --> 00:40:03.200
which is the first place
that people will go to find

00:40:03.200 --> 00:40:04.500
out about what was happening.

00:40:04.500 --> 00:40:06.780
And we had people really
close to the ground,

00:40:06.780 --> 00:40:09.530
really close to the event,
really close to the people

00:40:09.530 --> 00:40:13.160
or family members, getting online
and telling their stories in sort

00:40:13.160 --> 00:40:14.920
of these unmediated ways, right.

00:40:14.920 --> 00:40:19.050 position:56%
So, we wanted to think about ways to
get archivists and researchers sort

00:40:19.050 --> 00:40:23.470
of plugged into that
content and think about ways

00:40:23.470 --> 00:40:26.700
to do that easily for them.

00:40:26.700 --> 00:40:31.370
So, DocNow is basically
a project to build tools

00:40:31.370 --> 00:40:36.550
that archivists could use to easily
and easily is really important here

00:40:36.550 --> 00:40:39.910
because there are a lot of tools
available right now to do this work

00:40:39.910 --> 00:40:46.510
that don't-- that require sort of
this high level of technical skill

00:40:46.510 --> 00:40:49.400
to really get into and really
use sort of capture the data

00:40:49.400 --> 00:40:50.890
and make any sense of it.

00:40:50.890 --> 00:40:54.750
So, what we're doing is we're
building something that folks,

00:40:54.750 --> 00:40:57.510
you know, without any technical
skills, could just sort of tap into

00:40:57.510 --> 00:41:00.520
and start making some sense out of
this sort of vast amount of data,

00:41:00.520 --> 00:41:03.910
right, millions of
tweets in some cases.

00:41:03.910 --> 00:41:08.180
So, building tools to capture
that data, to export metadata,

00:41:08.180 --> 00:41:14.530
