01:16:00.590 --> 01:16:02.710
that actually does
get what they're doing

01:16:02.710 --> 01:16:06.790
and to make the path
easier for them.

01:16:06.790 --> 01:16:08.090
&gt;&gt; Bergis Jules: So, you know,

01:16:08.090 --> 01:16:09.620
I think the surveillance
thing is going

01:16:09.620 --> 01:16:12.330
to become real challenge
for archives.

01:16:12.330 --> 01:16:17.130
People have been doing
traditional archiving pretty soon.

01:16:17.130 --> 01:16:23.190 position:56%
So, when Ed Summers and I were
collecting social media on Ferguson,

01:16:23.190 --> 01:16:27.110
and he posted about his, I think
it was almost 14 million tweets

01:16:27.110 --> 01:16:29.530
that he had collected on Ferguson.

01:16:29.530 --> 01:16:33.230
He wrote a blog post about
it and posted it online.

01:16:33.230 --> 01:16:37.050 position:56%
You know, one of the first people to
reach out to Ed was a security firm,

01:16:37.050 --> 01:16:40.540
right, who had also been collecting
on Ferguson, but they had missed

01:16:40.540 --> 01:16:43.380
that window that we
had the data for.

01:16:43.380 --> 01:16:46.830
So they wanted Ed to share
that data with them, right.

01:16:46.830 --> 01:16:51.430
And so, people are out
there watching, right.

01:16:51.430 --> 01:16:57.070
Law enforcement is watching
and we know that, you know,

01:16:57.070 --> 01:16:59.740
when these tools, that law
enforcement bill gets put

01:16:59.740 --> 01:17:03.320
into place, they disproportionately
target poor people

01:17:03.320 --> 01:17:04.620
and people of color.

01:17:04.620 --> 01:17:05.920
That's just what happens.

01:17:05.920 --> 01:17:09.370 position:56%
I think no matter what the sort of
reasoning is, what's about terrorism

01:17:09.370 --> 01:17:14.460 position:56%
or whatever, whatever is sort of the
justification is at first to sort

01:17:14.460 --> 01:17:19.260
of justify the use of the stuff,
it always ends up being sort

01:17:19.260 --> 01:17:20.560
of marginalized groups

01:17:20.560 --> 01:17:23.470
or disproportionately affected
by these types of tools.

01:17:23.470 --> 01:17:26.740
And so, I think, you know,
archivists, you know,

01:17:26.740 --> 01:17:29.980
we've been sort of
operating and, you know,

01:17:29.980 --> 01:17:31.750 position:56%
in the sort of closed spaces, right,

01:17:31.750 --> 01:17:34.030
with paper records
for a very long time.

01:17:34.030 --> 01:17:36.040
We sort of own that space.

01:17:36.040 --> 01:17:40.260
We sort of decide what happens
in that space, who gets access.

01:17:40.260 --> 01:17:43.400
But as we move into this
sort of digital space

01:17:43.400 --> 01:17:46.410 position:56%
where really we're dealing with
data, right, and we call it archives

01:17:46.410 --> 01:17:49.160
and all this stuff, but we're
dealing with data and metadata

01:17:49.160 --> 01:17:51.790
and other people can
tap into that, right?

01:17:51.790 --> 01:17:54.320
We no longer have control
of these types

01:17:54.320 --> 01:17:56.980
of archives that we're building.

01:17:56.980 --> 01:17:58.600
So I think we really need to think

01:17:58.600 --> 01:18:02.280 position:56%
about as we're building these
collections of data, how we're going

01:18:02.280 --> 01:18:06.080
to protect people that represented
in there and we're not even close

01:18:06.080 --> 01:18:07.380
to thinking about that yet.

