And so, fighting this impulse,
aggressively fighting the impulse

03:08:09.320 --> 03:08:14.240
of archival obscurity, you know,
to the other extreme of suddenly,

03:08:14.240 --> 03:08:16.020
we've got all of the stuff online,

03:08:16.020 --> 03:08:19.550
you wouldn't believe the takedown
requests that we're getting now.

03:08:19.550 --> 03:08:21.170
It's really astonishing.

03:08:21.170 --> 03:08:23.450
I'm so jazzed about discovery.

03:08:23.450 --> 03:08:28.250
I'm so excited that more and more
people are using our materials.

03:08:28.250 --> 03:08:30.220
But it is interesting.

03:08:30.220 --> 03:08:31.590
I love the calls, "Hey, I can--

03:08:31.590 --> 03:08:33.380
I found my grandfather,
great grandfather.

03:08:33.380 --> 03:08:34.680
I've never heard his voice.

03:08:34.680 --> 03:08:35.980
This is great."

03:08:35.980 --> 03:08:41.530
But also getting calls
like, "What the hell?

03:08:41.530 --> 03:08:45.700
You know, I had no idea my life
story was going to be, you know,

03:08:45.700 --> 03:08:47.840
bullet pointed to the
great degree of detail

03:08:47.840 --> 03:08:52.040 position:56%
and be the number two search hit if
you Google, when you search my name.

03:08:52.040 --> 03:08:53.580
I'm applying for jobs.

03:08:53.580 --> 03:08:54.880
What's going on?"

03:08:54.880 --> 03:08:58.100
I had a call just a couple of
months ago from a woman, totally,

03:08:58.100 --> 03:09:00.000
totally innocuous interview.

03:09:00.000 --> 03:09:01.830
I mean, it's a great interview.

03:09:01.830 --> 03:09:03.130
There's nothing in there

03:09:03.130 --> 03:09:06.720
that anybody would really possibly
think would be problematic.

03:09:06.720 --> 03:09:08.870
And the reality-- I called her.

03:09:08.870 --> 03:09:10.170
I-- We-- I said, "Do you mind

03:09:10.170 --> 03:09:12.580
if I ask you some questions
why you want this taken down?"

03:09:12.580 --> 03:09:13.970
Because all that she
gave me was this vague,

03:09:13.970 --> 03:09:17.990
"I'm reevaluating my
privacy, my online privacy."

03:09:17.990 --> 03:09:19.810
And so I called her
and talked to her.

03:09:19.810 --> 03:09:21.110
She's dating.

03:09:21.110 --> 03:09:24.180
And she said two men
actually quote back to her

03:09:24.180 --> 03:09:27.200
from her oral history
interview in first dates.

03:09:27.200 --> 03:09:30.590
And she said that's not supposed
to happen in a first date.

03:09:31.920 --> 03:09:33.830
And I said, "I agree.

03:09:33.830 --> 03:09:35.840
I'll take it down."

03:09:35.840 --> 03:09:39.540
And I think that's a great example.

03:09:39.540 --> 03:09:43.160
I have all kinds of examples
of so many, you know,

03:09:43.160 --> 03:09:45.550
from one our projects
who is HIV positive.

03:09:45.550 --> 03:09:48.010
And now, he's on the job market, he
doesn't want people to know that.

03:09:48.010 --> 03:09:49.310
And at the time he
did this interview,

03:09:49.310 --> 03:09:50.820
he really wanted to talk about it.

03:09:50.820 --> 03:09:52.120
But now, he doesn't
want it out there

03:09:52.120 --> 03:09:56.810 position:56%
and have it be the number two search
hit when you're searching Google.

03:09:56.810 --> 03:10:01.390
So we've had to really step
back I think pretty profoundly

03:10:01.390 --> 03:10:03.480
and think not just
about informed consent

03:10:03.480 --> 03:10:05.050
because we really need
to a better job of this.

03:10:05.050 --> 03:10:09.620
Because no matter what we're
saying to our people right now,

03:10:09.620 --> 03:10:11.340
it's not enough that
people that we're recording.

03:10:11.340 --> 03:10:17.780
And I know, we can't truly capture
the breadth of all that can happen

03:10:17.780 --> 03:10:20.890
to your interview, but we need
to do a better job and strive

03:10:20.890 --> 03:10:23.040
to do a better job
with informed consent.

03:10:23.040 --> 03:10:25.270
We need to do a better job
with informed accessioning too.

03:10:25.270 --> 03:10:28.160
Our archives need to know
what we have in these things.

03:10:28.160 --> 03:10:33.210
And so, one of the reasons we've
really put a lot of emphasis

03:10:33.210 --> 03:10:35.860
on indexing is we're able
to identify those things

03:10:35.860 --> 03:10:38.470
because indexing requires
deep engagement in thinking

03:10:38.470 --> 03:10:42.420
about the content, not just
mechanically transcribing something

03:10:42.420 --> 03:10:44.980
or even automatically
transcribing something.

03:10:44.980 --> 03:10:46.280
I'm the same as everybody.

03:10:46.280 --> 03:10:48.190
I would love to have automatic
speech recognition be the

03:10:48.190 --> 03:10:49.490
greatest thing.

03:10:49.490 --> 03:10:53.260
Right now, it is challenging
for oral history for a variety

03:10:53.260 --> 03:10:55.090 position:56%
of reasons, which we can talk about.

03:10:55.090 --> 03:11:00.390
But it also disconnects the
human element from the process

03:11:00.390 --> 03:11:01.790
and there's nothing more personal

03:11:01.790 --> 03:11:04.070
than this oral history
thing, I think.

03:11:04.070 --> 03:11:06.410
It's not historic photographs
from the '30s.

03:11:06.410 --> 03:11:07.730
This is somebody's life story

03:11:07.730 --> 03:11:10.340
and when you take a good
oral history interview

03:11:10.340 --> 03:11:12.030
that says, where were you born?

03:11:12.030 --> 03:11:13.500
Let's talk about your parents.

03:11:13.500 --> 03:11:17.030
Where did you go to school?

03:11:17.030 --> 03:11:18.330
You get their email address.

03:11:18.330 --> 03:11:19.850
You just reset their bank password.

03:11:19.850 --> 03:11:22.900
We need to think about this
thing that we're collecting

03:11:22.900 --> 03:11:25.730
and the implications
of it down the road.

03:11:25.730 --> 03:11:29.930
I think we've solved a lot of
the problems here on the backend.

03:11:29.930 --> 03:11:35.010
Now, we need to think about the
implications of our solutions.

03:11:35.010 --> 03:11:36.310
&gt;&gt; Nicole Saylor: Great.

03:11:36.310 --> 03:11:38.790
&gt;&gt; Doug Boyd: That was just good.

03:11:38.790 --> 03:11:40.090
&gt;&gt; Nicole Saylor: Yeah.

03:11:40.090 --> 03:11:41.390
Come on over.

03:11:41.390 --> 03:11:42.690
&gt;&gt; Doug Boyd: I'll just sit here.

03:11:42.690 --> 03:11:43.990
&gt;&gt; Nicole Saylor: Sure.

03:11:43.990 --> 03:11:45.290
&gt;&gt; Doug Boyd: All right.

03:11:45.290 --> 03:11:46.590
Do we sit this close and talk?

03:11:46.590 --> 03:11:47.890
&gt;&gt; Nicole Saylor: Sure.

03:11:47.890 --> 03:11:49.190
&gt;&gt; Doug Boyd: OK.

03:11:49.190 --> 03:11:50.490
&gt;&gt; Nicole Saylor: I can
move over if it's weird.

03:11:50.490 --> 03:11:56.490
OK. So the American Folklife Center
sent out some spoken word materials

03:11:56.490 --> 03:12:02.130 position:56%
to participate in a project that
the New York Public Library is doing

03:12:02.130 --> 03:12:05.050
with the Pop Up Archive
and Moth, right?

03:12:05.050 --> 03:12:10.300
So they are sending a lot of spoken
word materials to Pop Up Archive,

03:12:10.300 --> 03:12:15.480
which then turns it in to text
and brings it back to you.

03:12:15.480 --> 03:12:18.590
So we participated in an
experiment with our materials

03:12:18.590 --> 03:12:21.070
and it actually turned out decent.

03:12:21.070 --> 03:12:23.380
I mean, it's not bad.

03:12:23.380 --> 03:12:28.800 position:56%
But-- so for people who are managing
large oral history collections,

03:12:28.800 --> 03:12:34.040
what kind of advice do you have for
looking at that, looking at OHMS

03:12:34.040 --> 03:12:36.300
and sort of carving a path?

03:12:36.300 --> 03:12:38.720
&gt;&gt; Doug Boyd: Well, I think
there's a lot of systems out there

03:12:38.720 --> 03:12:40.060
that do a lot of different things.

03:12:40.060 --> 03:12:42.700
And, you know, one of the
things I like about OHMS is

03:12:42.700 --> 03:12:45.280
that I don't have a
dog in the fight.

03:12:45.280 --> 03:12:48.330
I don't really care
actually if anybody uses it.

03:12:48.330 --> 03:12:50.520
I mean, other institutions,
you know.

03:12:50.520 --> 03:12:54.850
It's something that we gave away,
but we love using it in-house.

03:12:54.850 --> 03:12:59.360
And I'm excited to see it
empowering other archives.

03:12:59.360 --> 03:13:01.850
But what it's done for us
is pretty transformative.

03:13:01.850 --> 03:13:05.760
I think just from the
perspective of indexing,

03:13:05.760 --> 03:13:10.640
we indexed last year
900 hours of interview

03:13:10.640 --> 03:13:15.260
in a single year for
my student budget.

03:13:15.260 --> 03:13:17.580
No grant, no special initiative.

03:13:17.580 --> 03:13:19.710 position:56%
My student budget was about $16,000.

03:13:19.710 --> 03:13:23.520
Now, we don't pay very well
in Kentucky of our students.

03:13:23.520 --> 03:13:27.840
But for $16,000, we accomplished
what would've cost us probably

03:13:27.840 --> 03:13:31.520
$180,000 in a transcript model.

03:13:31.520 --> 03:13:34.130
That's pretty revolutionary for us.

03:13:34.130 --> 03:13:37.800
And so, we are now putting
most of our emphasis on that.

03:13:37.800 --> 03:13:40.120
And I think a lot of people
are doing it sort of thinking

03:13:40.120 --> 03:13:43.970
about this is an index now, maybe
transcribe later or maybe we clean

03:13:43.970 --> 03:13:47.150
up the automatic speech
recognition that really still even

03:13:47.150 --> 03:13:51.420
when it's pretty good requires
a lot of attention and care

03:13:51.420 --> 03:13:56.270 position:56%
and feeding I think in order to
bring it up to standards with regard

03:13:56.270 --> 03:13:59.410
to having it be a verbatim
transcripts.

03:13:59.410 --> 03:14:02.290
But I really start to
rethink my views on that.

03:14:02.290 --> 03:14:03.590
&gt;&gt; Nicole Saylor: Yeah.

03:14:03.590 --> 03:14:06.380
&gt;&gt; Doug Boyd: I'm staring to think
about transcripts less and less

03:14:06.380 --> 03:14:09.390
as the thing and more and more
as just the descriptive metadata.

03:14:09.390 --> 03:14:15.240
And when we make that paradigm
shift, it removes the burden

03:14:15.240 --> 03:14:17.200
of perfection completely.

03:14:17.200 --> 03:14:20.820
So we're going to start
experimenting with the idea

03:14:20.820 --> 03:14:25.720
of taking some of the ugly,
automatically generated speech

03:14:25.720 --> 03:14:31.460
to text material and kind of make
it searchable but not readable.

03:14:31.460 --> 03:14:33.580
Make it part of the search things

03:14:33.580 --> 03:14:35.220
because some of it
can be really bad.

03:14:35.220 --> 03:14:36.910
&gt;&gt; Nicole Saylor: But hide
it, right, on the interface.

03:14:36.910 --> 03:14:38.210
&gt;&gt; Doug Boyd: But hide it.

03:14:38.210 --> 03:14:39.700
Make it searchable, hidden,
but make it something

03:14:39.700 --> 03:14:42.770
that then can maybe connect to
a corresponding index point.

03:14:42.770 --> 03:14:46.640 position:56%
So we're thinking a great deal about
that and starting to experiment more

03:14:46.640 --> 03:14:47.940
and more with speech recognition.

03:14:47.940 --> 03:14:50.280
I love the idea of it.

03:14:50.280 --> 03:14:52.630
The idea of automating the
whole system, you know,

03:14:52.630 --> 03:14:55.710
is something that I think
makes me somewhat uncomfortable

03:14:55.710 --> 03:14:58.860
from a usability or from
an ethical standpoint

03:14:58.860 --> 03:15:03.310
of not knowing what we're putting
out on the internet when we do it.

03:15:03.310 --> 03:15:04.610
&gt;&gt; Nicole Saylor: Right.

03:15:04.610 --> 03:15:07.050
I mean, I think, you've
touched on it briefly, but yeah,

03:15:07.050 --> 03:15:10.280
how do you navigate than
tension between scaling access

03:15:10.280 --> 03:15:13.430
to these materials and also
being responsible stewards

03:15:13.430 --> 03:15:15.720
and it would seem like indexing
does give you a certain amount

03:15:15.720 --> 03:15:17.020
of check, right?

03:15:17.020 --> 03:15:18.500
&gt;&gt; Doug Boyd: We've
created a system, you know,

03:15:18.500 --> 03:15:21.940
I called it informed accessioning
and it's basically six questions

03:15:21.940 --> 03:15:24.680
that I have-- used to have
all my interviewers ask

03:15:24.680 --> 03:15:28.070
that basically all boil down to,
is there anything I need to know

03:15:28.070 --> 03:15:30.810
about this in here and
if this were your story,

03:15:30.810 --> 03:15:32.700
would you mind it going
online next week?

03:15:32.700 --> 03:15:34.000
And--

03:15:34.000 --> 03:15:35.530
&gt;&gt; Nicole Saylor: So you asked
that during the interview, right?

03:15:35.530 --> 03:15:37.800
&gt;&gt; Doug Boyd: The interviewers
are asking themselves--

03:15:37.800 --> 03:15:39.100
&gt;&gt; Nicole Saylor: Oh I see.

03:15:39.100 --> 03:15:40.400
&gt;&gt; Doug Boyd: -- this question
when they write out our forms.

03:15:40.400 --> 03:15:41.700
&gt;&gt; Nicole Saylor: When they're
working on an interview, got it.

03:15:41.700 --> 03:15:43.000
&gt;&gt; Doug Boyd: Yeah.

03:15:43.000 --> 03:15:44.670
And there's turning in paperwork
for our interview and kind

03:15:44.670 --> 03:15:46.700
of telling us, hey, you
need to look at this.

03:15:46.700 --> 03:15:50.460
But I started having the indexers
do it because we started realizing

03:15:50.460 --> 03:15:54.430 position:56%
that we have all this legacy content
that's not being collected yesterday

03:15:54.430 --> 03:15:58.920
or tomorrow, that we have
very little amount of data for

03:15:58.920 --> 03:16:04.020
and again repeatedly finding really
profound examples of people talking

03:16:04.020 --> 03:16:07.920 position:56%
about very personal things that just
have no, no business being online

03:16:07.920 --> 03:16:10.920
or actually having-- you
know, being quite problematic

03:16:10.920 --> 03:16:12.460
if they were to go online.

03:16:12.460 --> 03:16:15.750
So building in the workflows
where all the indexers, you know,

03:16:15.750 --> 03:16:21.000
are closely considering these
questions I think has really done a

03:16:21.000 --> 03:16:22.790
good job.

03:16:22.790 --> 03:16:25.660
We're teetering of the brink
of potentially being, you know,

03:16:25.660 --> 03:16:29.800
overwhelmed of suddenly we
had an influx of new projects

03:16:29.800 --> 03:16:32.190
and we brought in 600
some interviews last year,

03:16:32.190 --> 03:16:35.740
which is about five or
600 is now our average.

03:16:35.740 --> 03:16:40.230
And much more than that
would push us to the point

03:16:40.230 --> 03:16:43.300
where I would need far more
staffing to be able to have

03:16:43.300 --> 03:16:51.940
that closely curated hands on,
really conscientious approach,

03:16:51.940 --> 03:16:54.760
which I think is worth
retaining for sure.

03:16:54.760 --> 03:16:57.460
&gt;&gt; Nicole Saylor: Well so that
leads me to a question about your,

03:16:57.460 --> 03:17:01.100
the future plans for
OHMS and how you're going

03:17:01.100 --> 03:17:03.840
to keep it sustainable
and make is sustainable?

03:17:03.840 --> 03:17:05.930
&gt;&gt; Doug Boyd: Well, I mean,
that's really popular,

03:17:05.930 --> 03:17:10.050
so I'm really excited about that,
but, you know, but that's the key,

03:17:10.050 --> 03:17:13.290
it needs to be more about--
not about us, and so,

03:17:13.290 --> 03:17:15.690
we're creating kind of a Jedi
council, I don't know what

03:17:15.690 --> 03:17:19.600
to call it yet, so I'm calling
it that, of institutions

03:17:19.600 --> 03:17:24.580
who have bought into it big, Yale,
University of Georgia has really

03:17:24.580 --> 03:17:27.960
into it big time, Brooklyn
Historical is into it.

03:17:27.960 --> 03:17:31.000
But really basically
creating a group of,

03:17:31.000 --> 03:17:34.610
a consortial group that's going
to decide and drive development.

03:17:34.610 --> 03:17:37.980
You know, we went ahead
and made it bilingual.

03:17:37.980 --> 03:17:41.350
I think there's a-- I'm
taking ideas right now,

03:17:41.350 --> 03:17:43.000
because I'm reaching the
point where it's time

03:17:43.000 --> 03:17:46.020
to apply for another grant.

03:17:46.020 --> 03:17:48.470
And I think-- and I'm doing--

03:17:48.470 --> 03:17:50.870
I'm kicking around the idea
of actually having it--

03:17:50.870 --> 03:17:54.030
having, you know, and I think this
comes from my visit with Kevin

03:17:54.030 --> 03:17:55.500
and talking about-- Kevin Bradley,

03:17:55.500 --> 03:17:57.750
you're going to talk
here from this afternoon.

03:17:57.750 --> 03:18:02.630
We're really having a desktop
presence, you know, that's local,

03:18:02.630 --> 03:18:05.450
that's not-- doesn't
require media to be streaming

03:18:05.450 --> 03:18:09.390
so that people can index restricted
material and feel safe about it.

03:18:09.390 --> 03:18:12.840
But also have the interviewers,
and this is me always thinking

03:18:12.840 --> 03:18:14.450
about workflow and efficiency.

03:18:14.450 --> 03:18:15.870
If I can have interviewers

03:18:15.870 --> 03:18:20.630
who are indexing material offline
before it even comes to the archive

03:18:20.630 --> 03:18:23.530
and I'm accessioning material.

03:18:23.530 --> 03:18:27.120
It has this level of structured
metadata, that's a dream.

03:18:27.120 --> 03:18:28.420
&gt;&gt; Nicole Saylor: Yeah.

03:18:28.420 --> 03:18:31.120
&gt;&gt; Doug Boyd: So, that's kind
of where I'm leaning right now.

03:18:31.120 --> 03:18:32.420
&gt;&gt; Nicole Saylor: Cool.

