their broadcast online.

03:20:21.110 --> 03:20:26.420
Time text is essentially text with
markup language and that, you know,

03:20:26.420 --> 03:20:27.790
tells you what the timing is.

03:20:27.790 --> 03:20:34.360
It's a standard that came from the
W3C, the World Wide Web Consortium

03:20:34.360 --> 03:20:36.620
and then it was further
standardized by [inaudible]

03:20:36.620 --> 03:20:39.700
in the United States
and EBU in Europe.

03:20:39.700 --> 03:20:42.090
So, it's a way that will now come

03:20:42.090 --> 03:20:46.670
in to the way broadcasts
are synchronized.

03:20:46.670 --> 03:20:52.370 position:56%
Is there anything about that that
is helpful to you or vice versa or--

03:20:52.370 --> 03:20:53.670
&gt;&gt; Doug Boyd: Absolutely.

03:20:53.670 --> 03:20:54.970
I mean, one of my--

03:20:54.970 --> 03:20:56.270
&gt;&gt; Talk about that a little bit.

03:20:56.270 --> 03:20:57.570
That would be great.

03:20:57.570 --> 03:20:58.870
&gt;&gt; Doug Boyd: First I want to
say you're only just a slightly--

03:20:58.870 --> 03:21:00.630
you're only slightly
less intimidating now

03:21:00.630 --> 03:21:03.120
that you're retired.

03:21:03.120 --> 03:21:05.580
So, so so.

03:21:05.580 --> 03:21:10.600
&gt;&gt; [inaudible] but he's
still intimidating.

03:21:10.600 --> 03:21:11.900
&gt;&gt; Doug Boyd: Right.

03:21:11.900 --> 03:21:14.510 position:56%
I think when we first started on the
OHMS journey, it really bugged me

03:21:14.510 --> 03:21:16.690
that there wasn't a good
reference point for that.

03:21:16.690 --> 03:21:19.850
And now that we're
pretty far into it,

03:21:19.850 --> 03:21:25.200
one of my obsessions is how can we
connect it to a greater standard

03:21:25.200 --> 03:21:27.010
with regard to time and text.

03:21:27.010 --> 03:21:29.920
And so that's definitely
something over the first year,

03:21:29.920 --> 03:21:35.120
that's one of the first mandates
really of the Jedi council,

03:21:35.120 --> 03:21:37.070
you know, the people
who we've put together.

03:21:37.070 --> 03:21:40.600
I shouldn't keep-- I shouldn't
have said that publicly, sorry.

03:21:40.600 --> 03:21:44.340
But basically, the group, that's
one of the top priorities,

03:21:44.340 --> 03:21:48.900
is how can we take this now and
fit it better into standards

03:21:48.900 --> 03:21:51.700
that are starting to
emerge and that's the one

03:21:51.700 --> 03:21:53.430
that everybody is talking
about really.

03:21:53.430 --> 03:21:54.730
&gt;&gt; Thank you.

03:21:54.730 --> 03:21:56.500
&gt;&gt; Doug Boyd: At least in my circle
that we're all talking about.

03:21:56.500 --> 03:22:00.130
&gt;&gt; Well [inaudible]
is great because each

03:22:00.130 --> 03:22:02.380
of those would reinforce
each other and so on

03:22:02.380 --> 03:22:05.310
and you'd get a broader
adoption and so on.

03:22:05.310 --> 03:22:08.510
I mean, it's what we dream
of when we talk of standards.

03:22:08.510 --> 03:22:10.080
Too often, it doesn't work.

03:22:10.080 --> 03:22:11.390
But sometimes it does.

03:22:11.390 --> 03:22:12.690
&gt;&gt; Doug Boyd: Right.

03:22:12.690 --> 03:22:14.820
Hashtag motion jpeg 2000.

03:22:14.820 --> 03:22:17.210
We've got to get that one too.

03:22:17.210 --> 03:22:19.950
But I think if we can really--

03:22:19.950 --> 03:22:23.400
and I really am not a fan
of reinventing the wheel.

03:22:23.400 --> 03:22:25.420
You know, and that's
one of my frustrations

03:22:25.420 --> 03:22:28.310
with digital humanities is this
impulse to create something nifty

03:22:28.310 --> 03:22:31.060 position:56%
and cool but again, not sustainable,

03:22:31.060 --> 03:22:34.530
not something that has
necessarily broad appeal.

03:22:34.530 --> 03:22:37.520
And so, we really have to I
think work together and rather

03:22:37.520 --> 03:22:39.930
than reinvent the wheel,
really start to connect.

03:22:39.930 --> 03:22:44.060
So, that's right in line with
where we're going with that.

03:22:44.060 --> 03:22:46.070
&gt;&gt; I wanted to ask you.

03:22:46.070 --> 03:22:47.660
This may be a little tangential,

03:22:47.660 --> 03:22:51.180
but a lot of cultural heritage
archives are using crowd sourcing

03:22:51.180 --> 03:22:54.240
in order to do transcriptions, and
I see that with natural history,

03:22:54.240 --> 03:22:59.170
I see that with cultural materials,
see that with sociological stuff

03:22:59.170 --> 03:23:02.850
but what is your experience or
do you think there's a future

03:23:02.850 --> 03:23:07.550 position:56%
for crowd sourcing in audio recorded
interviews or oral histories?

03:23:07.550 --> 03:23:10.560
&gt;&gt; Doug Boyd: I think
particular early history is

03:23:10.560 --> 03:23:12.280
where I have an opinion.

03:23:12.280 --> 03:23:16.620 position:56%
And that-- a strong opinion, and
that's really a lot of our material,

03:23:16.620 --> 03:23:20.390
if it's going to be transcribed,
we don't know what's in it.

03:23:20.390 --> 03:23:25.830
And I have an-- a real discomfort
necessarily turning what I don't

03:23:25.830 --> 03:23:28.820
know is in there out to a crowd.

03:23:28.820 --> 03:23:32.140
Also, I have a discomfort opening
up the way my collection is going

03:23:32.140 --> 03:23:35.010
to be described to people
who actually are commenting

03:23:35.010 --> 03:23:38.040
on news stories about the
presidential election this year.

03:23:38.040 --> 03:23:40.840
You know, I mean anybody, just
opening it up and saying, you know,

03:23:40.840 --> 03:23:44.640
another certain ways we can
actually vet that automatically,

03:23:44.640 --> 03:23:45.970 position:56%
but there are certain ways we can't.

03:23:45.970 --> 03:23:50.880
And so, I'm a little nervous about
just opening the doors to that.

03:23:50.880 --> 03:23:54.650
And so, I'd rather have sort
of a curated form of that.

03:23:54.650 --> 03:24:00.190
Also, you need the crowd and
transcription is not a fun act.

03:24:00.190 --> 03:24:04.940 position:56%
No matter how you video game the
experience, I think, you either need

03:24:04.940 --> 03:24:10.370
to make it so partial that
it's not a big deal and so it's

03:24:10.370 --> 03:24:14.630
like the CAPTCHAs with
the home addresses.

03:24:14.630 --> 03:24:18.430
You know, or you need a
crowd that's just so massive.

03:24:18.430 --> 03:24:21.100
And so, I don't have that crowd.

03:24:21.100 --> 03:24:24.550
I can get-- I can walk into a room

03:24:24.550 --> 03:24:26.860
and get people excited
about indexing.

03:24:26.860 --> 03:24:28.160
Because it's actually fun.

03:24:28.160 --> 03:24:30.850 position:56%
It's actually engaging and that's
why we're getting all these students

03:24:30.850 --> 03:24:33.850
doing it in classrooms,
we're starting to experiment

03:24:33.850 --> 03:24:36.120
with volunteer groups
who are stakeholders

03:24:36.120 --> 03:24:39.330
in a particular project, who are
going to actually play a role

03:24:39.330 --> 03:24:41.760
on how this project gets
represented publicly.

03:24:41.760 --> 03:24:44.410
But to just sort of
open the doors wide,

03:24:44.410 --> 03:24:47.890 position:56%
it's not really what I'm leaning
towards right now because the nature

03:24:47.890 --> 03:24:50.480
of our oral and history
collection and because it's sort

03:24:50.480 --> 03:24:54.580
of the trust arrangement
we have with the people

03:24:54.580 --> 03:24:56.370
who were interviewed originally.

03:24:56.370 --> 03:25:00.280
Or a trust relationship
that the interviewer had

03:25:00.280 --> 03:25:01.990
but then gave the collection
to an archive

03:25:01.990 --> 03:25:03.350
that doesn't have that
trust relationship.

03:25:03.350 --> 03:25:09.010
So we're trying to be good
stewards of this process on my end.

03:25:09.010 --> 03:25:10.870
Someone's going to
take OHMS and do that.

03:25:10.870 --> 03:25:12.920
They're just going to open up
the doors and turn it again

03:25:12.920 --> 03:25:15.200
into a true sort of crowd
sourcing platform and I think

03:25:15.200 --> 03:25:16.750
that will work pretty cool.

03:25:16.750 --> 03:25:19.300
But, you know, I like
what NYPL has done

03:25:19.300 --> 03:25:21.810
with their transcription
tool for sure.

03:25:21.810 --> 03:25:24.310
I think if you haven't messed
with it, it's super cool.

